WEBVTT

1
00:00:02.780 --> 00:00:06.260
[breath exhaling]

2
00:00:10.540 --> 00:00:12.300
[flag rustling]

3
00:00:12.380 --> 00:00:15.180
[fireworks crackling]

4
00:00:32.420 --> 00:00:35.260
[thunder rumbling]

5
00:00:37.900 --> 00:00:39.540
[thunder cracks]

6
00:00:41.900 --> 00:00:45.420
[waves lapping]

7
00:00:58.220 --> 00:01:03.780
[wood creaking]
[man grunting]

8
00:01:15.380 --> 00:01:19.220
[man speaking Spanish]
<i>Capitan! Capitan!</i>

9
00:01:31.580 --> 00:01:32.620
[grunts]

10
00:01:37.540 --> 00:01:39.100
Who are you?

11
00:01:50.740 --> 00:01:52.940
[horses panting]

12
00:01:57.420 --> 00:01:58.500
[man shouts indistinctly]

13
00:02:02.460 --> 00:02:04.220
[man shouting indistinctly]

14
00:02:32.780 --> 00:02:34.060
What is this?

15
00:02:34.140 --> 00:02:37.580
Your Majesty, caught him
up in a fishing net.
A fishing net.

16
00:02:37.660 --> 00:02:41.220
Sire, he's been telling
stories. Stories that...
We believe he's found a...

17
00:02:49.340 --> 00:02:51.380
Ponce de Leon.

18
00:02:53.700 --> 00:02:55.980
Says he found
Ponce de Leon's ship.

19
00:02:56.100 --> 00:02:58.900
[man 2] Or sailed on it.
[man 1] No, I told you,

20
00:02:58.980 --> 00:03:00.740
Ponce de Leon
died 200 years ago.

21
00:03:00.820 --> 00:03:04.140
Aye, but he died searching
for something, didn't he?

22
00:03:07.340 --> 00:03:09.260
The Fountain of Youth.

23
00:03:14.220 --> 00:03:16.140
How soon can you sail?

24
00:03:17.260 --> 00:03:18.740
With the tide.

25
00:03:37.740 --> 00:03:39.260
[woman] Over here!
Lucky heather!

26
00:03:39.340 --> 00:03:42.140
[man] Pirate swords!
Pirate swords!

27
00:03:42.300 --> 00:03:45.420
Pirate's execution today.
Watch him swing!

28
00:03:45.500 --> 00:03:47.780
[man] Pirate puppets!

29
00:03:47.860 --> 00:03:51.100
Take that, you!
[girl] Hurry, Papa,
or we'll miss the hanging!

30
00:03:51.180 --> 00:03:54.860
It's not a hanging, dear,
it's a trial. The hanging
comes this afternoon.

31
00:03:54.940 --> 00:03:56.780
[man] Pirate hanging today!

32
00:03:56.900 --> 00:04:02.420
[door creaks]
Come on. Up you get.

33
00:04:02.500 --> 00:04:04.780
Move along, pirate.

34
00:04:04.900 --> 00:04:09.020
Or should I say,
"Captain Pirate"? [laughs]

35
00:04:09.100 --> 00:04:12.020
Come on. Come on! Up you go.

36
00:04:12.100 --> 00:04:14.300
[crowd shouting]
[man] Quiet! Order!

37
00:04:14.380 --> 00:04:17.740
[pounding gavel]
[man] Quiet!

38
00:04:17.820 --> 00:04:20.460
Now appearing
before the court,

39
00:04:20.540 --> 00:04:23.340
the notorious and infamous
pirate, pillager,

40
00:04:23.460 --> 00:04:24.620
and highwayman...
Quiet!

41
00:04:24.700 --> 00:04:26.740
...Captain Jack Sparrow!

42
00:04:27.460 --> 00:04:30.460
[crowd jeering]

43
00:04:30.540 --> 00:04:34.420
I told you, the name's Gibbs!
Joshamee Gibbs!

44
00:04:34.500 --> 00:04:37.980
How many times...
[man] Hear ye, hear ye!
Presiding over these trials,

45
00:04:38.140 --> 00:04:43.580
all rise and attend, the
Right Honorable Justice Smith!

46
00:04:44.260 --> 00:04:46.780
[crowd shouting]

47
00:04:53.380 --> 00:04:54.900
My dear sir.

48
00:04:58.780 --> 00:05:01.740
Quiet!
[pounding gavel]

49
00:05:01.860 --> 00:05:04.060
Now...

50
00:05:05.020 --> 00:05:06.700
...what do we have here?

51
00:05:07.380 --> 00:05:08.420
Jack?

52
00:05:08.500 --> 00:05:10.020
Shut up!
[grunts]

53
00:05:10.100 --> 00:05:12.100
[crowd chattering]
I don't recognize him.

54
00:05:12.260 --> 00:05:15.460
Not necessary.
You were saying?

55
00:05:15.580 --> 00:05:17.820
Jack Sparrow is not my name.

56
00:05:17.900 --> 00:05:20.220
My name is Joshamee Gibbs.
[crowd shouting]

57
00:05:20.300 --> 00:05:21.980
Is that so?

58
00:05:22.060 --> 00:05:25.100
It says Jack Sparrow here.
[Gibbs] I told 'em.

59
00:05:25.180 --> 00:05:28.540
I'm not Jack Sparrow,
who I would be happy
to identify to the court

60
00:05:28.620 --> 00:05:31.740
if it would help my case.
I think that would
be a poor defense,

61
00:05:31.820 --> 00:05:34.420
unless you want
to be bludgeoned again
like a harp seal.

62
00:05:34.620 --> 00:05:37.860
[crowd shouting]
[Jack] The prisoner
claims of being innocent

63
00:05:37.940 --> 00:05:40.220
to being Jack Sparrow.
How do you find?

64
00:05:40.860 --> 00:05:43.220
No trial? But aren't we here
to examine the evidence...

65
00:05:43.340 --> 00:05:45.900
Foreman, your finding. Guilty?

66
00:05:46.020 --> 00:05:47.580
Guilty verdict
means he'll hang.

67
00:05:47.660 --> 00:05:51.580
[crowd cheering]
Hang him! String him up!

68
00:05:51.700 --> 00:05:54.340
[crowd quiets]

69
00:05:54.420 --> 00:05:55.940
Guilty?
That's not fair!

70
00:05:56.020 --> 00:05:57.780
[crowd cheering]
Shut it.

71
00:05:57.900 --> 00:05:59.100
[pounds gavel]

72
00:05:59.180 --> 00:06:01.140
Joshamee Gibbs,
the crime of which

73
00:06:01.220 --> 00:06:02.740
you've been found guilty of

74
00:06:02.820 --> 00:06:05.340
is being innocent
of being Jack Sparrow.

75
00:06:06.580 --> 00:06:08.700
I hereby
commute your sentence,

76
00:06:08.780 --> 00:06:10.420
and order
that you be imprisoned
for the remainder

77
00:06:10.540 --> 00:06:14.180
of your miserable, moribund,
mutton-chopped life.

78
00:06:14.300 --> 00:06:15.820
What?!
Hang him!

79
00:06:15.900 --> 00:06:18.220
[woman] Hang him!
There.

80
00:06:18.300 --> 00:06:21.380
Balderdash!
String him up!
Hang him high!

81
00:06:21.500 --> 00:06:22.380
[clamoring]

82
00:06:22.460 --> 00:06:25.300
Means shall be arranged
to transport this prisoner

83
00:06:25.420 --> 00:06:27.660
to the Tower of London.

84
00:06:36.580 --> 00:06:38.660
[muffled shouting]

85
00:06:38.740 --> 00:06:40.060
Thanks very much.

86
00:06:44.580 --> 00:06:45.900
Ta.

87
00:06:49.500 --> 00:06:52.180
Come on. Get up there.

88
00:06:54.580 --> 00:06:56.100
Get up!

89
00:07:00.660 --> 00:07:04.620
Hell's teeth. Now we're
both headed for prison.

90
00:07:04.700 --> 00:07:07.700
Not to worry.
I've paid off the driver.

91
00:07:07.820 --> 00:07:11.060
Ten minutes, we'll be outside
London Town, horses waiting.

92
00:07:11.140 --> 00:07:12.620
Tonight, we make the coast.

93
00:07:12.700 --> 00:07:14.540
Then it's just a matter
of finding a ship.

94
00:07:16.380 --> 00:07:18.940
[Gibbs] All part
of the plan, yes?
[Jack] Exactly.

95
00:07:19.020 --> 00:07:21.020
I arrived in London Town
just this morning

96
00:07:21.100 --> 00:07:22.620
to rescue one
Joshamee Gibbs

97
00:07:22.700 --> 00:07:24.460
from one appointment
with the gallows.

98
00:07:24.540 --> 00:07:26.260
Seeing as how
you're still alive,

99
00:07:26.340 --> 00:07:29.340
I'd say it's all been
very successful thus far.

100
00:07:29.780 --> 00:07:31.420
What happened
to you, Gibbs?

101
00:07:31.500 --> 00:07:34.300
I thought you were
employed elsewhere
or otherwise engaged.

102
00:07:34.380 --> 00:07:37.980
Aye. But I always listened
like a thief for news
of the <i>Black Pearl.

103
00:07:38.060 --> 00:07:40.260
Nobody's seen where
she might next make port.

104
00:07:40.380 --> 00:07:42.340
Then, I hear a rumor:

105
00:07:42.420 --> 00:07:46.020
Jack Sparrow's in London
with a ship and looking
for a crew.

106
00:07:46.100 --> 00:07:47.780
Am not.
But that's what I heard.

107
00:07:47.860 --> 00:07:50.460
Fact is, you're
signing up men tonight.

108
00:07:50.540 --> 00:07:52.020
Pub called
The Captain's Daughter.

109
00:07:52.140 --> 00:07:55.540
Am not!
Well, I thought it
a bit odd,

110
00:07:55.620 --> 00:07:59.180
but then, you've never
been the most predictable
of sorts.

111
00:07:59.820 --> 00:08:02.460
Tell me something.
There is another

112
00:08:02.540 --> 00:08:05.020
Jack Sparrow out there
sullying my good name?

113
00:08:05.100 --> 00:08:07.380
An impostor.
Indeed.

114
00:08:07.500 --> 00:08:11.140
But... an impostor
with a ship.

115
00:08:11.220 --> 00:08:13.340
And in need of a crew.

116
00:08:14.060 --> 00:08:15.980
Which, as fate
would have it, so am I.

117
00:08:17.020 --> 00:08:18.420
What about you, Jack?

118
00:08:18.500 --> 00:08:20.580
Last I heard
you were hell-bent

119
00:08:20.700 --> 00:08:22.780
to find
the Fountain of Youth.

120
00:08:23.180 --> 00:08:24.300
Any luck?

121
00:08:26.340 --> 00:08:29.540
Circumstances arose
and forced
a compelling insight

122
00:08:29.620 --> 00:08:31.580
regarding discretion
and valor.

123
00:08:31.700 --> 00:08:34.660
Meaning, you gave up.
I did not.

124
00:08:34.740 --> 00:08:37.780
I am just as bent as ever.
Hellishly so.

125
00:08:37.900 --> 00:08:42.620
I shall taste those waters,
Master Gibbs. Mark my words.

126
00:08:44.700 --> 00:08:46.780
Oh. Short trip.
[chuckles]

127
00:08:55.900 --> 00:08:57.580
All part
of the plan, yes?

128
00:08:59.260 --> 00:09:02.140
[grunts] No.

129
00:09:29.340 --> 00:09:31.900
[door closes, locks]

130
00:09:33.140 --> 00:09:35.500
[footsteps receding]

131
00:09:35.580 --> 00:09:37.460
[horses trotting, neighing]

132
00:09:37.540 --> 00:09:39.340
[distant chattering]

133
00:09:41.620 --> 00:09:45.100
[distant banging]

134
00:09:54.180 --> 00:09:55.780
[grunts]

135
00:10:00.060 --> 00:10:02.780
[marching footsteps approach]

136
00:10:30.820 --> 00:10:34.140
You are Jack Sparrow?

137
00:10:34.260 --> 00:10:36.940
There should be a "Captain"
in there somewhere.

138
00:10:37.060 --> 00:10:38.900
I've heard of you.

139
00:10:39.740 --> 00:10:41.740
And you know who I am.

140
00:10:42.500 --> 00:10:45.340
Face is familiar.
Have I threatened you before?

141
00:10:45.420 --> 00:10:49.020
You are in the presence
of George Augustus,
Duke of Brunswick-Luneburg,

142
00:10:49.100 --> 00:10:52.260
Archtreasurer
and Prince-elector
of the Holy Roman Empire,

143
00:10:52.340 --> 00:10:55.740
King of Great Britain
and Ireland, and of you.

144
00:10:57.180 --> 00:10:59.460
Doesn't ring a bell.
I am informed

145
00:10:59.540 --> 00:11:04.220
you have come to London
to procure a crew
for your ship.

146
00:11:04.340 --> 00:11:06.580
Vicious rumor. Not true.

147
00:11:06.740 --> 00:11:09.780
Then you lied to me when you
told me you were Jack Sparrow.

148
00:11:09.860 --> 00:11:13.100
I am Jack Sparrow, but I'm
not here to procure a crew.

149
00:11:13.180 --> 00:11:15.540
That is... someone else.

150
00:11:15.620 --> 00:11:20.900
Ah. Someone else
named Jack Sparrow.

151
00:11:20.980 --> 00:11:23.260
You've brought me
the wrong wastrel.

152
00:11:23.380 --> 00:11:26.700
Find the proper one
and dispose of this impostor.

153
00:11:26.780 --> 00:11:28.780
No, wait, wait.
Hang on a minute.

154
00:11:28.940 --> 00:11:31.300
I'm Jack Sparrow,
the one and only.

155
00:11:31.380 --> 00:11:32.860
And I am in London.

156
00:11:32.940 --> 00:11:35.620
To procure a crew.
[chains clanking loudly]

157
00:11:35.700 --> 00:11:38.420
To undertake a voyage
to the Fountain...
What?

158
00:11:38.500 --> 00:11:42.420
Will someone please remove
these infernal chains?

159
00:11:42.540 --> 00:11:45.940
[sighs] Come, come.
[chains clanking]

160
00:11:47.380 --> 00:11:49.940
We know you're
in possession of a map.

161
00:11:50.060 --> 00:11:53.300
So confiscate the map,
and to the gallows with him!

162
00:11:53.380 --> 00:11:55.100
Have you a map?

163
00:12:00.260 --> 00:12:02.700
No.
Where is it?

164
00:12:02.780 --> 00:12:06.020
The truth? I lost it.

165
00:12:06.580 --> 00:12:10.340
Quite recently, in fact.
I have a report.

166
00:12:10.420 --> 00:12:14.180
The Spanish have located
the Fountain of Youth.

167
00:12:14.260 --> 00:12:19.340
I will not have some
melancholy Spanish monarch,

168
00:12:19.580 --> 00:12:24.180
a Catholic,
gain eternal life!

169
00:12:24.300 --> 00:12:26.100
[silverware clattering]

170
00:12:26.180 --> 00:12:28.860
You do know the way
to the Fountain?

171
00:12:28.980 --> 00:12:31.140
Of course I do.
Look at me.

172
00:12:31.260 --> 00:12:33.020
You could guide
an expedition.

173
00:12:35.100 --> 00:12:37.100
With your permission,
your heinie,

174
00:12:37.860 --> 00:12:40.220
you will be providing,
then, a ship...

175
00:12:42.220 --> 00:12:43.620
...and a crew?

176
00:12:43.740 --> 00:12:46.460
And a captain.

177
00:13:01.380 --> 00:13:04.300
Afternoon, sire.

178
00:13:05.300 --> 00:13:09.220
If I may be so bold,
why is that man not
in chains?

179
00:13:09.300 --> 00:13:11.500
He must be
manacled at once.

180
00:13:11.580 --> 00:13:15.140
At the center
of my palace? Hardly.

181
00:13:15.580 --> 00:13:16.940
Hector.

182
00:13:17.420 --> 00:13:20.980
How nice to see
a fellow pirate
make good of himself.

183
00:13:21.060 --> 00:13:23.980
Pirate? Nay. Privateer.

184
00:13:24.060 --> 00:13:30.220
On a sanctioned mission
under the authority and
protection of the Crown.

185
00:13:30.380 --> 00:13:32.740
As may be, but first,

186
00:13:33.700 --> 00:13:36.220
what has become of
my beloved <i>Pearl?

187
00:13:36.340 --> 00:13:39.460
I lost the Pearl
<i>as I lost my leg.</i>

188
00:13:39.540 --> 00:13:41.900
Lost the Pearl?
<i>Aye.</i>

189
00:13:42.020 --> 00:13:45.820
I defended
her mightily enough,
but she be sunk nonetheless.

190
00:13:52.300 --> 00:13:56.060
If that ship
be sunk properly,
you should be sunk with it.

191
00:13:56.180 --> 00:14:01.780
Captain Barbossa,
each second we tarry,
the Spanish outdistance us.

192
00:14:01.860 --> 00:14:04.500
I have every confidence
you will prevail
and be rewarded

193
00:14:04.580 --> 00:14:07.540
with the high station
you so desire.

194
00:14:07.660 --> 00:14:12.340
To serve doth suffice, sire.
You, sir, have stooped.

195
00:14:13.180 --> 00:14:15.700
Jack, our sands
be all but run.

196
00:14:15.780 --> 00:14:19.020
Where's the harm in
joining the winning side?

197
00:14:19.100 --> 00:14:22.940
And you do meet
a nicer class of person.

198
00:14:23.420 --> 00:14:25.220
I understand everything.

199
00:14:27.020 --> 00:14:28.420
Except that wig.

200
00:14:34.780 --> 00:14:37.500
[man] He's getting away!
Stop him!

201
00:14:37.580 --> 00:14:40.940
[man 2] Head him off!
[man 3] No!
Stop that pirate!

202
00:14:41.060 --> 00:14:44.660
[men shouting indistinctly]

203
00:15:03.700 --> 00:15:05.140
Come down!

204
00:15:14.380 --> 00:15:18.300
He escaped?
Leave it to me, sire.

205
00:15:23.500 --> 00:15:26.780
Guards! Guards!

206
00:15:43.220 --> 00:15:46.620
[horse whinnies]
[people chattering
indistinctly]

207
00:15:49.700 --> 00:15:52.260
Arms at ready!
Sir!

208
00:15:58.900 --> 00:16:00.540
Find him!

209
00:16:13.460 --> 00:16:14.580
[whistle trilling]

210
00:16:22.580 --> 00:16:24.420
Finders keepers!

211
00:16:24.860 --> 00:16:25.980
There!

212
00:16:28.380 --> 00:16:29.500
[grunts]

213
00:16:37.940 --> 00:16:39.220
[shrieks]

214
00:16:43.060 --> 00:16:44.140
Oh...

215
00:16:44.260 --> 00:16:45.100
[gasps]

216
00:16:45.220 --> 00:16:46.820
[sighs]

217
00:16:49.620 --> 00:16:50.820
Is that it?

218
00:16:53.540 --> 00:16:54.900
Oh!

219
00:16:54.980 --> 00:16:57.620
[man] Halt!
Stop that carriage!

220
00:16:57.740 --> 00:16:58.900
[man 2] Head him off!

221
00:17:05.300 --> 00:17:07.900
[soldiers shouting
indistinctly]

222
00:17:08.060 --> 00:17:10.500
Out of the way!
[horse whinnies]

223
00:17:26.180 --> 00:17:27.580
[whinnies]

224
00:17:36.740 --> 00:17:38.540
[man] Stop that pirate!

225
00:17:38.660 --> 00:17:40.220
[clamoring]

226
00:17:40.380 --> 00:17:42.420
[man] Move out of the way!

227
00:17:47.980 --> 00:17:50.220
[grunts]
[man] Stop that man!

228
00:17:50.340 --> 00:17:51.660
[grunts]

229
00:17:51.780 --> 00:17:52.980
[man] Don't let him get away!

230
00:17:53.100 --> 00:17:55.140
[man 2] Hi-yah! Hi-yah!

231
00:18:01.100 --> 00:18:03.540
Fire!
[grunts]

232
00:18:09.380 --> 00:18:10.540
[grunts]

233
00:18:29.660 --> 00:18:34.180
Whoa! He's getting away!
After him! Stop him!

234
00:18:36.780 --> 00:18:38.300
After him!

235
00:18:41.180 --> 00:18:43.260
[sign creaking]

236
00:18:43.340 --> 00:18:45.500
[distant buoy bell clangs]

237
00:18:47.180 --> 00:18:48.700
[seagulls crying]

238
00:18:48.780 --> 00:18:51.140
[man] Filthy pirate.

239
00:18:51.220 --> 00:18:53.180
[gun cocks]

240
00:18:53.260 --> 00:18:55.500
[gun fires]
[grunts]

241
00:19:01.340 --> 00:19:03.300
Hello, Jackie.

242
00:19:06.340 --> 00:19:07.900
Hello, Dad.

243
00:19:08.020 --> 00:19:10.380
Whoo! [laughs]
[up-tempo music plays]

244
00:19:10.500 --> 00:19:12.900
[snoring]
[laughter]

245
00:19:15.660 --> 00:19:18.500
[Teague] I heard you're
putting together a crew.

246
00:19:18.580 --> 00:19:21.620
If enough people keep
saying it, it must be true.

247
00:19:21.740 --> 00:19:24.540
I heard where you're headed.
The Fountain.

248
00:19:24.700 --> 00:19:26.060
Have you been there?

249
00:19:26.700 --> 00:19:30.220
Does this face look like it's been
to the Fountain of Youth?

250
00:19:31.660 --> 00:19:34.860
Depends on the light.
Son, the Fountain.

251
00:19:34.940 --> 00:19:38.780
There'll be items required
for the profane ritual.

252
00:19:38.860 --> 00:19:40.660
Two chalices.

253
00:19:41.180 --> 00:19:42.980
On the map
there was a chalice.

254
00:19:43.060 --> 00:19:44.780
Two, silver.

255
00:19:44.860 --> 00:19:47.900
From the Ponce de Leon ship.
You'll need both.

256
00:19:48.700 --> 00:19:51.660
For?
The ritual.
Don't be a fool, Jackie.

257
00:19:51.780 --> 00:19:54.780
Find out every detail
before you set sail.

258
00:19:54.860 --> 00:19:56.740
Oh, set sail. Love to.

259
00:19:56.820 --> 00:19:59.260
But for that,
I may need a ship.

260
00:19:59.700 --> 00:20:02.660
Those folk, over there,
they have a ship.

261
00:20:02.780 --> 00:20:04.980
They're signing up
sailors right now.

262
00:20:05.060 --> 00:20:07.540
<i>♪ My heart</i>
<i>is pierced by Cupid ♪</i>

263
00:20:07.660 --> 00:20:09.860
<i>♪ I disdain all</i>
<i>glittering gold ♪</i>

264
00:20:09.980 --> 00:20:12.300
And one
last thing, Jackie.

265
00:20:13.380 --> 00:20:16.460
The Fountain will test you.
Mark my words.

266
00:20:16.580 --> 00:20:18.140
<i>♪ My heart</i>
<i>is pierced by Cupid ♪</i>

267
00:20:18.220 --> 00:20:19.980
<i>♪ I disdain all</i>
<i>glittering gold ♪</i>

268
00:20:20.060 --> 00:20:23.060
<i>♪ There is nothing</i>
<i>can console me ♪</i>

269
00:20:23.140 --> 00:20:26.060
<i>♪ But my jolly sailor bold ♪</i>

270
00:20:26.220 --> 00:20:28.780
[laughter]

271
00:20:39.100 --> 00:20:41.380
I hear you been
recruiting a crew.

272
00:20:41.660 --> 00:20:43.700
Aye. That is,

273
00:20:43.820 --> 00:20:47.140
Jack Sparrow be putting
together a modest venture.

274
00:20:49.860 --> 00:20:51.500
You got some nerve,
ain't ya?

275
00:20:51.580 --> 00:20:53.820
Turning up here
dressed like that?

276
00:20:53.900 --> 00:20:55.740
What are you,
some kind of impostor?

277
00:20:55.820 --> 00:20:57.820
Have you any idea
who I am, mate?

278
00:20:58.580 --> 00:20:59.860
[cackles]

279
00:20:59.940 --> 00:21:01.660
Oi, muckers!

280
00:21:01.740 --> 00:21:04.300
There's a bloke here what's
forgotten his own name!

281
00:21:04.380 --> 00:21:06.580
[jeering laughter]
[door opens]

282
00:21:07.060 --> 00:21:09.340
[man] Lads,
I'm sailing with Sparrow.

283
00:21:09.420 --> 00:21:11.500
Who'll buy
a sailor a drink?

284
00:21:11.580 --> 00:21:14.380
[cheering]

285
00:21:14.460 --> 00:21:15.980
[man] Who's next?

286
00:21:23.500 --> 00:21:26.580
[man] Bring us
some more of those ones.

287
00:21:26.700 --> 00:21:27.980
Yeah, make it four.

288
00:21:37.380 --> 00:21:40.980
You've stolen me, and I'm
here to take meself back.

289
00:22:14.940 --> 00:22:16.180
Stop doing that.

290
00:22:27.780 --> 00:22:29.020
[grunts]

291
00:22:42.580 --> 00:22:43.300
[grunts]

292
00:22:55.500 --> 00:22:58.660
[creaking]

293
00:23:25.020 --> 00:23:26.140
[swords clanking]

294
00:23:27.980 --> 00:23:28.860
[grunts]

295
00:23:48.300 --> 00:23:51.140
Only one person alive
knows that move.

296
00:23:54.060 --> 00:23:55.420
[gasps]

297
00:23:58.940 --> 00:24:00.660
Always wanted to do that.

298
00:24:01.900 --> 00:24:03.420
Hello, Angelica.

299
00:24:03.500 --> 00:24:04.780
[gasps]

300
00:24:06.140 --> 00:24:09.940
Hello, Jack.
Are you impressed?

301
00:24:10.500 --> 00:24:13.500
I think I almost killed you
once or twice there.

302
00:24:13.620 --> 00:24:17.260
I'm touched at this most
sincerest form of flattery.

303
00:24:18.700 --> 00:24:20.020
But why?

304
00:24:21.300 --> 00:24:24.540
You were the only pirate
I thought I would pass for.

305
00:24:24.660 --> 00:24:26.460
That is not a compliment.

306
00:24:26.580 --> 00:24:28.340
[buttons clattering]

307
00:24:28.460 --> 00:24:32.180
Don't worry, Jack.
I forgave you
a long time ago.

308
00:24:32.300 --> 00:24:36.780
For what? For leaving you?
Recall that I left you.

309
00:24:37.940 --> 00:24:41.300
A gentleman allows a lady
to maintain her fictions.

310
00:24:41.660 --> 00:24:45.140
Look, Sparrow. As long as
my sailors get their money,

311
00:24:45.220 --> 00:24:48.340
they're willing
to put up with any number
of peculiarities.

312
00:24:48.420 --> 00:24:50.420
Ah. There is
one peculiarity

313
00:24:50.500 --> 00:24:52.460
with which I will
not put up with.

314
00:24:53.660 --> 00:24:56.900
I will be impersonated
as "Captain." Nothing less.

315
00:24:57.020 --> 00:24:58.940
Well, for that,
you need a ship,

316
00:24:59.060 --> 00:25:01.540
and as it turns out,
I have one.

317
00:25:01.980 --> 00:25:03.820
I could use a ship.

318
00:25:04.100 --> 00:25:06.900
I hear tell you've
been to the Fountain.

319
00:25:06.980 --> 00:25:09.740
There be a lot
of hear-telling
going on these days.

320
00:25:09.860 --> 00:25:13.900
The Fountain of Youth.
Dearest Angelica, fret not.

321
00:25:13.980 --> 00:25:17.180
You still have
a few usable years left.

322
00:25:17.260 --> 00:25:20.620
[chuckles]
Always so charming.

323
00:25:20.700 --> 00:25:22.220
You didn't answer me.
Eh?

324
00:25:22.300 --> 00:25:24.660
Aye. Regarding the Fountain.
Waste of time, really...

325
00:25:24.740 --> 00:25:26.900
[man] Milady, I see
unseamanlike fellows

326
00:25:27.020 --> 00:25:28.540
of an officious-looking
nature.

327
00:25:28.620 --> 00:25:31.180
[man] Wretched pirates!
Find 'em! Maggots!

328
00:25:31.260 --> 00:25:32.660
[men shouting]

329
00:25:34.580 --> 00:25:36.420
[pounding on door]
Friends of yours?

330
00:25:36.500 --> 00:25:39.460
I may have unintentionally
slighted some king or other.

331
00:25:39.580 --> 00:25:41.380
[man] Open it!
[pounding]

332
00:25:41.500 --> 00:25:44.260
Yeah, you haven't changed.
Implying the need?

333
00:25:44.740 --> 00:25:45.460
Yes.

334
00:25:45.580 --> 00:25:47.220
[man] Open this door,
in the name of His Majesty.

335
00:25:47.300 --> 00:25:50.820
You betrayed me.
You seduced me
and you used me.

336
00:25:50.900 --> 00:25:52.940
I was innocent
of the ways of men.

337
00:25:53.020 --> 00:25:56.300
You demonstrated a lot
of technique for someone
I supposedly corrupted.

338
00:25:56.460 --> 00:25:59.020
Imminent danger.
Here, now, milady!

339
00:25:59.100 --> 00:26:00.060
[man] Open it!

340
00:26:01.420 --> 00:26:04.700
I was ready to take my vows.
And you...

341
00:26:04.820 --> 00:26:07.500
What were you doing in
a Spanish convent, anyway?

342
00:26:07.620 --> 00:26:09.900
Mistook it for a brothel.
Honest mistake.

343
00:26:09.980 --> 00:26:12.300
[pounding]
[men shouting]

344
00:26:13.660 --> 00:26:14.980
There he is!
Over there!

345
00:26:15.100 --> 00:26:17.220
[grunting]

346
00:26:17.300 --> 00:26:20.380
[indistinct shouting]

347
00:26:34.380 --> 00:26:35.860
We are at a disadvantage.

348
00:26:35.940 --> 00:26:39.500
Speak for yourself.
Unlike some who pretend
to be,

349
00:26:39.580 --> 00:26:41.900
but cannot, in fact,
hold a candle to,

350
00:26:41.980 --> 00:26:43.860
I am
Captain Jack Sparrow.

351
00:27:17.500 --> 00:27:20.020
[gasping]

352
00:27:20.100 --> 00:27:22.740
How can you say
I used you?

353
00:27:23.260 --> 00:27:25.380
You know exactly how.

354
00:27:25.460 --> 00:27:28.540
I know, but how
can you say it?

355
00:27:28.620 --> 00:27:30.060
[growls]

356
00:27:30.220 --> 00:27:33.020
[distant buoy bell clanging]

357
00:27:33.100 --> 00:27:36.180
[Angelica] So, what is it?
[Jack] What is what?

358
00:27:36.580 --> 00:27:38.340
About the Fountain.

359
00:27:40.900 --> 00:27:42.380
What do you know?

360
00:27:43.580 --> 00:27:45.660
You don't happen
to be in possession

361
00:27:45.780 --> 00:27:49.060
of two silver chalices,
circa Ponce de Leon?

362
00:27:49.580 --> 00:27:51.580
No.
Ha. Thought not.

363
00:27:51.660 --> 00:27:55.300
Why?
I hear stories.

364
00:27:55.620 --> 00:27:56.780
Rumors.

365
00:27:57.580 --> 00:27:59.620
You are, of course,
aware of the ritual.

366
00:28:00.420 --> 00:28:01.620
Yes, I am.

367
00:28:01.700 --> 00:28:02.540
Hmm.

368
00:28:04.020 --> 00:28:06.540
What is it?
What is required?

369
00:28:06.620 --> 00:28:08.700
[projectile whizzes]
[grunts]

370
00:28:09.580 --> 00:28:10.820
Hmm?

371
00:28:11.460 --> 00:28:13.340
A mermaid, Jack.

372
00:28:19.660 --> 00:28:20.980
[dog barking]

373
00:28:21.060 --> 00:28:22.540
[Gibbs]
There's been a mistake.

374
00:28:22.620 --> 00:28:27.100
It's a life sentence,
not death. Life!

375
00:28:31.380 --> 00:28:34.900
Barbossa.
Thank you, gentlemen.

376
00:28:35.380 --> 00:28:38.020
I trust
you can tie a noose.

377
00:28:38.100 --> 00:28:39.500
That's a hard thing,

378
00:28:40.140 --> 00:28:43.380
forcing a man to twist
his own hanging rope.

379
00:28:43.740 --> 00:28:46.660
You must lie in your bed
the way you made it.

380
00:28:48.140 --> 00:28:49.780
What's happened to you?

381
00:28:49.860 --> 00:28:53.500
Where be Jack Sparrow?
He escaped. [chuckles]

382
00:28:53.580 --> 00:28:55.300
I'm on a tight
schedule, Gibbs.

383
00:28:55.380 --> 00:28:57.580
The HMS Providence
<i>sets sail at first light,</i>

384
00:28:57.700 --> 00:29:00.180
and if you do not care
to watch it,
hanging here dead,

385
00:29:00.260 --> 00:29:02.340
with a mouth full of flies...

386
00:29:03.340 --> 00:29:05.220
...speak now.

387
00:29:06.420 --> 00:29:09.540
Take me with you.
Any point of the compass...

388
00:29:09.660 --> 00:29:14.540
Take you where, Gibbs?
The Fountain? Aye?

389
00:29:14.980 --> 00:29:17.180
Is that where
Jack be headed?

390
00:29:17.820 --> 00:29:20.900
Have you anything
you can offer me, Gibbs?

391
00:29:21.620 --> 00:29:23.420
Anything at all?

392
00:29:25.340 --> 00:29:28.660
Upon me naked word,
you'll not see the dawn.

393
00:29:28.780 --> 00:29:30.460
[rope creaking]

394
00:29:36.700 --> 00:29:38.460
Hand it over.

395
00:29:42.860 --> 00:29:45.620
You fool!
I had just enough time

396
00:29:45.820 --> 00:29:48.220
to study those
infernal circles.

397
00:29:48.300 --> 00:29:53.500
Every route,
every destination.
All safe... in here.

398
00:29:53.940 --> 00:29:56.860
Welcome back
to His Majesty's navy,

399
00:29:56.940 --> 00:29:58.420
Master Gibbs.

400
00:30:05.660 --> 00:30:08.420
[waves crashing]
[wood creaking]

401
00:30:08.500 --> 00:30:10.860
[snoring]

402
00:30:10.940 --> 00:30:13.020
[grunts]
[man] Show a leg, sailor!

403
00:30:13.100 --> 00:30:14.780
Aye, sir.

404
00:30:16.140 --> 00:30:17.420
What?

405
00:30:17.980 --> 00:30:19.820
[chickens clucking]
There's been
a horrible mistake.

406
00:30:19.900 --> 00:30:22.380
Keep moving.
[men shouting]

407
00:30:22.460 --> 00:30:25.540
I'm not supposed to be here.
Many a man's woken up
at sea,

408
00:30:25.620 --> 00:30:27.900
no idea what, when,
wherefore or why.

409
00:30:27.980 --> 00:30:29.900
No memory of the night afore,
whence he signed up

410
00:30:29.980 --> 00:30:31.780
and drank away
all his bonus money.

411
00:30:31.860 --> 00:30:33.660
No, no, no.
You don't understand, mate.

412
00:30:33.780 --> 00:30:36.380
I'm Captain Jack Sparrow.
The original. The only.

413
00:30:36.460 --> 00:30:39.500
Scrum, and the pleasure's
all mine. Now, keep moving.

414
00:30:40.900 --> 00:30:43.340
[distant chattering]

415
00:30:47.340 --> 00:30:48.980
Scrum.

416
00:30:49.060 --> 00:30:51.020
[man] Get your elbows in!

417
00:30:53.700 --> 00:30:55.900
Why is there a glass coffin?

418
00:30:56.380 --> 00:30:58.380
Do I look like
a man in charge?

419
00:30:58.620 --> 00:31:01.460
Where am I?
'Scuse me,
Captain Sparrow, sir.

420
00:31:01.540 --> 00:31:03.460
I be right honored
to welcome you aboard our

421
00:31:03.540 --> 00:31:07.060
world-renowned
vessel of infamy,
<i>Queen Anne's Revenge.</i>

422
00:31:10.100 --> 00:31:11.580
Blackbeard.

423
00:31:15.940 --> 00:31:19.180
[indistinct shouting]

424
00:31:28.180 --> 00:31:30.460
Work!
[screams]

425
00:31:33.260 --> 00:31:37.540
[Jack] He's a curious one.
[Scrum] He's been
zombiefied.

426
00:31:37.660 --> 00:31:40.180
Eh?
Zombiefied.

427
00:31:40.260 --> 00:31:43.820
Blackbeard's doing.
All the officers
are the same.

428
00:31:43.900 --> 00:31:47.060
Makes 'em more compliant.
[shouts]

429
00:31:47.180 --> 00:31:49.060
And perpetually ill-tempered.

430
00:31:50.580 --> 00:31:53.060
Come on. Scrub.
Yeah.

431
00:32:00.500 --> 00:32:04.060
[crew chanting]
Pull! Pull! Pull!

432
00:32:04.460 --> 00:32:06.820
[grunting]

433
00:32:08.700 --> 00:32:11.020
[Jack] Five days underway,
at least.

434
00:32:11.100 --> 00:32:14.740
Aye. You can tell that
by the smell of the sea?

435
00:32:15.180 --> 00:32:16.980
Smell of the crew.

436
00:32:19.420 --> 00:32:23.780
[seagulls crying]
[Jack] Oi. What did
that poor sod do?

437
00:32:23.900 --> 00:32:25.740
And how can I
make sure to not?

438
00:32:25.820 --> 00:32:28.100
Him? Churchly fellow.

439
00:32:28.180 --> 00:32:30.580
Always going on about
the Lord Almighty.

440
00:32:30.660 --> 00:32:32.340
Bible-thumper on this ship?

441
00:32:32.420 --> 00:32:34.260
A missionary
is his story.

442
00:32:34.340 --> 00:32:36.860
What I heard was
he got captured in a raid.

443
00:32:36.940 --> 00:32:40.060
Rest of the ship
got killed, but not 'im.

444
00:32:40.140 --> 00:32:41.820
First mate
wouldn't let it happen

445
00:32:41.900 --> 00:32:44.740
on account of his premier
standing with the Lord.

446
00:32:44.820 --> 00:32:48.740
A first mate sticking her
neck out for some prisoner.

447
00:32:48.820 --> 00:32:50.780
That you don't see.

448
00:32:50.860 --> 00:32:53.620
"Her"?
First mate is a "her"?

449
00:32:53.700 --> 00:32:55.540
[man] Back to work!

450
00:33:04.220 --> 00:33:05.980
Steady as she goes.

451
00:33:18.020 --> 00:33:20.780
[gasps]
[blade unsheathes]

452
00:33:20.860 --> 00:33:25.420
You are a ruthless,
soulless, cross-grained cur.

453
00:33:25.500 --> 00:33:29.260
I told you I had a ship.
No, Blackbeard has a ship,

454
00:33:29.340 --> 00:33:31.620
upon which I am
now imprisoned.

455
00:33:32.060 --> 00:33:33.940
We can do this, Jack.

456
00:33:34.020 --> 00:33:38.140
The Fountain of Youth,
like you always wanted.

457
00:33:38.700 --> 00:33:43.300
Blackbeard. Edward Teach.
The pirate all pirates fear.

458
00:33:43.740 --> 00:33:46.380
Resurrector of the dead
in his spare time.

459
00:33:46.460 --> 00:33:49.340
He will listen to me.
He listens to no one.

460
00:33:49.460 --> 00:33:52.060
Maybe to his own daughter?

461
00:33:54.700 --> 00:33:57.740
Daughter as in... beget by?

462
00:33:58.580 --> 00:34:02.180
Long-lost.
Recently found.

463
00:34:02.500 --> 00:34:05.860
Who loves her dear papa
with all her soul.

464
00:34:06.660 --> 00:34:08.660
He bought that?
I sold that.

465
00:34:08.780 --> 00:34:11.820
[footsteps approaching]

466
00:34:16.140 --> 00:34:17.860
Then it's the Fountain
of Youth for him,

467
00:34:17.940 --> 00:34:20.660
or him and you,
not you and me.

468
00:34:20.820 --> 00:34:23.220
No, Jack,
that's the best part.

469
00:34:23.580 --> 00:34:26.060
He will be dead.
Ah.

470
00:34:26.260 --> 00:34:29.140
You'll be handling
that part yourself, then?

471
00:34:29.260 --> 00:34:30.940
There is a prophecy.

472
00:34:31.220 --> 00:34:33.820
Maybe you don't believe
in the supernatural.

473
00:34:33.980 --> 00:34:36.300
Oh, no, no.
I've seen a thing or two.

474
00:34:38.940 --> 00:34:42.340
The prophecy is this:

475
00:34:43.140 --> 00:34:46.780
Blackbeard will
meet his death within
a fortnight

476
00:34:47.060 --> 00:34:49.820
at the hands
of a one-legged man.

477
00:34:50.180 --> 00:34:52.780
That's why he needs
the Fountain, Jack.

478
00:35:09.220 --> 00:35:11.660
[Barbossa] Oh, Master Gibbs,
short we are a map.

479
00:35:11.740 --> 00:35:15.100
Perhaps you'd be so kind
as to provide us an heading.

480
00:35:18.660 --> 00:35:20.980
Be a gem
and pour me a gulper.

481
00:35:21.060 --> 00:35:24.340
Nay. We be privateers,
not pirates, Master Gibbs.

482
00:35:24.420 --> 00:35:26.940
And in the king's name,
we behave as such.

483
00:35:27.260 --> 00:35:29.700
Aye, Captain.

484
00:35:33.020 --> 00:35:35.740
Be we on the
proper course, Gibbs?

485
00:35:35.820 --> 00:35:38.060
Aye, it be proper.

486
00:35:38.740 --> 00:35:40.660
There's your proof.

487
00:35:47.180 --> 00:35:48.540
The Spaniard.

488
00:35:49.740 --> 00:35:54.940
All hands! Battle stations!
Get to windward!

489
00:35:55.020 --> 00:35:57.740
[man] All hands, windward!
Harden up two points!

490
00:35:57.820 --> 00:36:01.620
[man] Two points!
Cast loose the cannons!

491
00:36:05.740 --> 00:36:09.180
Gunners, take posts!
[man] Take position!
Gunners ready, sir!

492
00:36:09.260 --> 00:36:13.340
Out! Thrust!
Await orders.

493
00:36:15.340 --> 00:36:16.820
[man] Steady!

494
00:36:18.140 --> 00:36:19.780
Guns armed,
awaiting orders, sir.

495
00:36:25.580 --> 00:36:29.100
Sir. Orders, sir?

496
00:36:35.580 --> 00:36:38.140
He never so much
as turned his head.

497
00:36:38.220 --> 00:36:40.580
The Fountain is the prize.

498
00:36:40.700 --> 00:36:44.340
It appears we be not
even worth the time
it'd take to sink us.

499
00:36:44.460 --> 00:36:48.380
And now we've fallen behind.
All hands, make more sail!

500
00:36:48.500 --> 00:36:50.700
All hands more sail!

501
00:36:50.780 --> 00:36:54.060
Ride hard between
wind and tide!

502
00:37:04.180 --> 00:37:07.540
The topic, gentlemen,
is mutiny.

503
00:37:08.780 --> 00:37:10.620
Mutiny most foul.

504
00:37:10.700 --> 00:37:14.380
Aye. I signed up to sail
under Jack Sparrow,
not some pretender.

505
00:37:14.500 --> 00:37:18.180
And a lady, at that.
And mention was failed to
be made of this uncanny crew.

506
00:37:18.260 --> 00:37:20.060
Make my toes curl, they do.

507
00:37:20.140 --> 00:37:23.660
[swords rattling]
I got 'em. All of 'em.

508
00:37:23.740 --> 00:37:25.580
[Jack] Well done.
Good lad.

509
00:37:25.900 --> 00:37:28.100
On to it, then.
Blackbeard.

510
00:37:28.380 --> 00:37:31.100
What are his habits?
Stays mostly to his cabin.

511
00:37:31.180 --> 00:37:33.580
That's right,
mostly to his cabin.

512
00:37:33.660 --> 00:37:37.020
Yes, but when
he comes out...
He don't really come out.

513
00:37:37.100 --> 00:37:40.700
[all muttering]
He must come out sometime.

514
00:37:41.460 --> 00:37:44.020
Not really, no.
[all muttering]

515
00:37:45.460 --> 00:37:47.340
Any of you
sail with him before?

516
00:37:47.420 --> 00:37:49.700
No, no. Definitely not.
I've never.

517
00:37:49.780 --> 00:37:53.940
Any of you seen him before?
Not really, no.

518
00:37:55.500 --> 00:37:57.860
Stays to his cabin,
no one sailed with him,

519
00:37:57.980 --> 00:37:59.340
no one's seen him...

520
00:37:59.980 --> 00:38:03.500
Good news, gentlemen.
This is not
Blackbeard's ship.

521
00:38:03.580 --> 00:38:05.660
This is not the
<i>Queen Anne's Revenge.</i>

522
00:38:05.820 --> 00:38:07.620
No, this be the
<i>Queen Anne's Revenge,</i>
right enough.

523
00:38:07.740 --> 00:38:08.980
How do you know?

524
00:38:09.060 --> 00:38:11.860
I've seen the name,
on the back of the ship.

525
00:38:15.580 --> 00:38:21.140
[Jack] Gentlemen, sirs,
fellow conscriptees...

526
00:38:22.260 --> 00:38:24.460
...you have been
monstrously deceived.

527
00:38:24.540 --> 00:38:27.860
We are decepted, then?
Yes.

528
00:38:28.820 --> 00:38:31.340
You've nay been informed
of a destination.

529
00:38:31.660 --> 00:38:33.900
Death lies before us

530
00:38:34.140 --> 00:38:38.900
as we sail for the
Fountain of Youth.

531
00:38:39.860 --> 00:38:42.620
[all muttering]
[Jack] It would be
a sorry plight, mates.

532
00:38:42.700 --> 00:38:46.340
Death, for certain.
The garden of
darkened souls.

533
00:38:46.420 --> 00:38:49.260
Untimely our ends will be.
Unless...

534
00:38:50.500 --> 00:38:52.340
...we take the ship.

535
00:38:53.940 --> 00:38:56.940
We take the ship, then. Now!

536
00:38:57.340 --> 00:38:59.700
[clattering]

537
00:39:01.860 --> 00:39:04.500
Go on, then.
[all yelling]

538
00:39:04.580 --> 00:39:06.940
Help me, shipmates!
Give it to 'em!

539
00:39:07.060 --> 00:39:09.100
Wake up! It's ours!
Come on!

540
00:39:09.180 --> 00:39:12.500
Get up! Off your backside!
[indistinct shouting]

541
00:39:12.580 --> 00:39:15.020
Get off your fannies!
Take it to them, lads!

542
00:39:15.180 --> 00:39:17.420
Help me! Fight!

543
00:39:29.860 --> 00:39:31.660
Mmm... Jack.

544
00:39:33.540 --> 00:39:37.820
If this is a dream, you can
keep the sword and boots on.

545
00:39:40.220 --> 00:39:42.780
If it's not...
It's a dream.

546
00:39:42.900 --> 00:39:45.260
[clamoring]

547
00:39:48.140 --> 00:39:49.540
No, it's not!

548
00:39:50.860 --> 00:39:52.140
I thought I should
give you fair warning,

549
00:39:52.220 --> 00:39:54.140
we're taking the ship.
[speaks Spanish]

550
00:39:54.220 --> 00:39:56.740
Nothing personal.
[speaking Spanish]

551
00:39:56.820 --> 00:39:58.540
Think you might be
better off if you just...

552
00:39:58.620 --> 00:40:01.740
[Angelica] Yah!
...stay out of it.

553
00:40:01.860 --> 00:40:04.260
[all yelling]

554
00:40:06.500 --> 00:40:09.060
[grunting]

555
00:40:16.900 --> 00:40:18.900
[growls]

556
00:40:24.260 --> 00:40:26.660
[roaring]
Boggit.

557
00:40:26.780 --> 00:40:28.540
[yells]

558
00:40:32.300 --> 00:40:33.500
[yells]

559
00:40:48.180 --> 00:40:49.580
[man] Wretch!

560
00:41:04.300 --> 00:41:05.740
[yells]

561
00:41:14.100 --> 00:41:15.620
[shouts]

562
00:41:19.060 --> 00:41:21.340
You're either with us
or against us!

563
00:41:21.420 --> 00:41:23.660
I am not with you,
neither am I against you!

564
00:41:23.780 --> 00:41:25.180
Can he do that?

565
00:41:25.300 --> 00:41:27.860
He's religious.
I believe it's required.

566
00:41:28.340 --> 00:41:30.060
[gasps, panting]

567
00:41:33.020 --> 00:41:36.540
Fight to the bitter end,
you cack-handed deck apes!

568
00:41:48.860 --> 00:41:51.060
Take him, men.
Tie him down tight!

569
00:41:59.660 --> 00:42:01.700
[grunting]

570
00:42:05.500 --> 00:42:07.020
The ship is ours!

571
00:42:23.660 --> 00:42:26.900
[sighs]
[wind whistling]

572
00:42:36.220 --> 00:42:38.100
Gentlemen.

573
00:42:46.060 --> 00:42:48.300
I be placed
in a bewilderment.

574
00:42:49.260 --> 00:42:52.740
There I were, resting,

575
00:42:53.900 --> 00:42:59.140
and upon a sudden, I hear
an ungodly row on deck.

576
00:43:00.580 --> 00:43:02.300
[sword vibrates]

577
00:43:02.380 --> 00:43:04.620
Sailors abandon their posts

578
00:43:04.700 --> 00:43:07.020
without orders,
without leave.

579
00:43:08.020 --> 00:43:10.660
Men before the mast,

580
00:43:11.260 --> 00:43:13.660
taking the ship
for themselves.

581
00:43:15.540 --> 00:43:17.860
What be that, First Mate?

582
00:43:17.980 --> 00:43:20.780
Mutiny, Captain.
Again?

583
00:43:20.860 --> 00:43:23.420
[Angelica] Mutiny!
Aye.

584
00:43:24.140 --> 00:43:25.860
Mutiny.

585
00:43:28.540 --> 00:43:32.220
And what fate
befalls mutineers?

586
00:43:32.340 --> 00:43:35.620
Now, we know the answer
to that, do we not?

587
00:43:35.740 --> 00:43:39.020
Mutineers hang!

588
00:43:40.180 --> 00:43:42.380
[all shouting]

589
00:43:48.860 --> 00:43:50.340
[shouting]

590
00:43:56.980 --> 00:43:58.500
[yells]

591
00:44:09.660 --> 00:44:11.460
Whoa!

592
00:44:29.100 --> 00:44:31.100
Captain, I wish
to report a mutiny.

593
00:44:32.180 --> 00:44:34.100
I can name fingers
and point names.

594
00:44:34.180 --> 00:44:35.980
No need, Mr. Sparrow.

595
00:44:36.060 --> 00:44:38.900
They are sheep.
You, their shepherd.

596
00:44:43.700 --> 00:44:46.780
Have I mentioned, sir,
what a lovely daughter
you have?

597
00:44:47.460 --> 00:44:51.100
A fitting last sight
for a doomed soul.
Remember, Father.

598
00:44:51.260 --> 00:44:53.980
We need him.
If I don't kill
a man every now and then,

599
00:44:54.100 --> 00:44:56.460
they forget who I am.
[man] Coward!

600
00:44:56.620 --> 00:44:59.980
Hmm?
They do not forget.

601
00:45:00.340 --> 00:45:03.420
Your crew sees you
for the miscreant you are.

602
00:45:03.500 --> 00:45:05.420
A coward, no matter
how many you slay.

603
00:45:05.500 --> 00:45:07.900
Twice in one day, I find
myself in a bewilderment.

604
00:45:07.980 --> 00:45:09.980
You are not bewildered,
you are afraid.

605
00:45:10.060 --> 00:45:13.260
You dare not walk the path
of righteousness,
the way of the light.

606
00:45:13.340 --> 00:45:16.780
No, sir. The truth is it
be much simpler than all that.

607
00:45:17.540 --> 00:45:19.420
I am a bad man.

608
00:45:19.620 --> 00:45:20.740
That, too.

609
00:45:20.860 --> 00:45:22.860
I might have to kill
you too, catechist.

610
00:45:22.980 --> 00:45:25.620
No!
All Latin blood
like her mother.

611
00:45:25.700 --> 00:45:27.460
Father, I beg you.

612
00:45:27.540 --> 00:45:31.380
Ah, there I be again,
forgetting why the
missionary is here.

613
00:45:31.820 --> 00:45:35.980
My daughter
fears for my soul,
or what's left of it.

614
00:45:37.020 --> 00:45:40.260
You truly wish to save me,
my child?

615
00:45:40.780 --> 00:45:42.980
Every soul can be saved.

616
00:45:43.740 --> 00:45:45.860
Be that true, young cleric?

617
00:45:45.940 --> 00:45:49.660
Yes. Though you I see
as a bit of a long shot.

618
00:45:50.580 --> 00:45:53.100
Still, I pray for
every unfortunate soul

619
00:45:53.180 --> 00:45:54.700
on this hell-bound vessel.

620
00:45:57.260 --> 00:45:59.820
You disarm me
with your faith.

621
00:46:00.980 --> 00:46:02.500
Eight bells!

622
00:46:02.580 --> 00:46:05.900
Which of you unfortunate
souls stood watch?

623
00:46:06.020 --> 00:46:10.740
I did. I stood watch.
[chuckles] Gunner.

624
00:46:15.940 --> 00:46:17.380
You?

625
00:46:18.060 --> 00:46:20.540
Aye.
[breathes heavily]

626
00:46:20.620 --> 00:46:22.420
[Blackbeard] Aye.

627
00:46:22.540 --> 00:46:27.420
The cook. Perfect.
Lower the longboat!

628
00:46:32.820 --> 00:46:34.420
Bring her about!

629
00:46:36.380 --> 00:46:38.420
[ship groans]

630
00:46:45.900 --> 00:46:49.420
Why do you do this?
Mutiny. Our laws be clear.

631
00:46:49.500 --> 00:46:51.860
Our laws allow the Captain
to show leniency.

632
00:46:51.940 --> 00:46:54.580
I have given this man
a chance to determine
his fate,

633
00:46:54.660 --> 00:46:56.300
a gift not afforded to all.

634
00:47:04.940 --> 00:47:07.060
Oh, you now.

635
00:47:07.660 --> 00:47:10.180
Chance to show the worth
of your prayers.

636
00:47:10.820 --> 00:47:14.980
Pray he be delivered
from... evil?

637
00:47:23.420 --> 00:47:26.660
Course made!
Stop. Give that man
a chance. Give yourself a...

638
00:47:28.500 --> 00:47:29.660
[screams]

639
00:47:52.060 --> 00:47:54.580
You know when I feel
closest to our Maker?

640
00:47:55.020 --> 00:47:57.100
When I see suffering,
pain and anguish.

641
00:47:57.220 --> 00:47:59.780
That's when the true design
of this world is revealed.

642
00:47:59.900 --> 00:48:03.580
And I see it revealed
when in times of hardship
and tragedy,

643
00:48:03.660 --> 00:48:06.020
kindness and compassion
are shown to those in need.

644
00:48:06.140 --> 00:48:08.580
Perhaps you should pray
for him to be unharmed, yes?

645
00:48:08.700 --> 00:48:10.740
Please, there's
still hope...
Again!

646
00:48:23.300 --> 00:48:25.980
I actually have no interest
in the Fountain whatsoever,

647
00:48:26.060 --> 00:48:28.660
so, if your heart is set,

648
00:48:28.740 --> 00:48:30.580
you may drop me off
anywhere you like.

649
00:48:30.660 --> 00:48:32.340
That'll be all, Quartermaster.

650
00:48:35.260 --> 00:48:38.420
Your words surround you like
fog and make you hard to see.

651
00:48:38.500 --> 00:48:42.380
And what of you,
the mighty Blackbeard?

652
00:48:42.460 --> 00:48:45.780
Beheaded they say.
Still, your body swam

653
00:48:45.860 --> 00:48:49.020
three times around your ship,
then climbed back on board.

654
00:48:49.100 --> 00:48:52.100
And here you are,
running scared.

655
00:48:52.700 --> 00:48:54.100
Scared.

656
00:48:54.540 --> 00:48:56.300
To the Fountain.

657
00:48:56.380 --> 00:48:59.220
[Blackbeard]
The Quartermaster sees
things before they happen.

658
00:48:59.300 --> 00:49:03.540
He has
foreseen my death, and so
the fates have spoken.

659
00:49:03.820 --> 00:49:06.140
The threads
of destiny woven.

660
00:49:06.220 --> 00:49:09.340
[Jack] You have a ridiculously
high regard for fate, mate.

661
00:49:09.420 --> 00:49:11.380
And you?
Me?

662
00:49:11.500 --> 00:49:15.620
I'm skeptical
of predicting any future...
which includes me.

663
00:49:15.980 --> 00:49:21.900
It'd be foolish
to battle fate, but I'd be
tempted to cheat it.

664
00:49:21.980 --> 00:49:24.540
I will reach the Fountain.
You will lead me.

665
00:49:26.980 --> 00:49:28.900
That knife will
serve you no better

666
00:49:28.980 --> 00:49:30.900
than the mutiny
you devised.

667
00:49:31.340 --> 00:49:32.980
Mutiny served me well.

668
00:49:33.060 --> 00:49:35.060
It gained me
an audience with you.

669
00:49:35.900 --> 00:49:38.140
Oh?
Aye.

670
00:49:39.700 --> 00:49:40.740
To warn you.

671
00:49:42.580 --> 00:49:44.060
Regarding your first mate,

672
00:49:44.180 --> 00:49:46.660
who pretends to be persons
she is not.

673
00:49:47.580 --> 00:49:48.700
Do tell.

674
00:49:51.140 --> 00:49:53.180
She is not your daughter.

675
00:49:56.180 --> 00:49:59.300
[Blackbeard] You dare
to speak thusly
of my flesh and blood?

676
00:49:59.380 --> 00:50:04.100
[Jack] Sir, the woman
is consummate in
the art of deception.

677
00:50:04.180 --> 00:50:08.820
I know.
As I mostly unwittingly
set her on her wicked path.

678
00:50:08.940 --> 00:50:11.300
Though I cannot
claim credit

679
00:50:11.420 --> 00:50:14.100
for her existing abundance
of natural talent.

680
00:50:15.980 --> 00:50:18.540
Angelica. [inhales]
My beloved daughter,

681
00:50:18.620 --> 00:50:21.020
the one true good thing
I have done in this life,

682
00:50:21.100 --> 00:50:23.940
and you claim to be the one
who corrupted her?

683
00:50:24.060 --> 00:50:28.100
Sir, what she is
is pure evil.

684
00:50:28.380 --> 00:50:30.700
More to be feared
than a wild beast.

685
00:50:30.780 --> 00:50:34.660
Hungry wild beast
with gnashing teeth.

686
00:50:34.740 --> 00:50:37.380
Vengeful, hungry
from hell beast...

687
00:50:37.460 --> 00:50:39.060
Father?
Sweetness!

688
00:50:39.180 --> 00:50:42.620
[groans]
[Angelica] No need
to hurt him, Father.

689
00:50:43.140 --> 00:50:46.060
He will help us.
Won't you, Jack?

690
00:50:46.180 --> 00:50:50.460
You see? Even now,
she attends to your welfare,

691
00:50:50.660 --> 00:50:53.260
giving lie to the claims
you make of her.

692
00:50:54.060 --> 00:50:55.180
[grunts]

693
00:51:00.980 --> 00:51:05.620
You will lead us
to the Fountain. Yes?

694
00:51:05.820 --> 00:51:08.100
[Blackbeard]
Put another way.

695
00:51:08.540 --> 00:51:12.780
If I do not make it
to the Fountain in time...

696
00:51:14.060 --> 00:51:16.940
...neither will you.
[fire sizzling]

697
00:51:18.900 --> 00:51:20.820
I'll have a wee look-see
at those charts

698
00:51:20.900 --> 00:51:22.900
straight away then, shall I?

699
00:51:26.820 --> 00:51:28.060
Sir.

700
00:51:30.860 --> 00:51:33.420
Aye?
Captain, sir,

701
00:51:33.540 --> 00:51:35.740
I am unhappy to
report rumors, sir,

702
00:51:35.820 --> 00:51:38.300
among the crew,
as to our destination.

703
00:51:39.100 --> 00:51:41.500
Shut your trap and make way.

704
00:51:42.020 --> 00:51:43.340
[sighs]

705
00:51:45.300 --> 00:51:49.500
That's the way of it, then.
No disrespect, sir.

706
00:51:49.580 --> 00:51:52.700
What do the men fear?
Say it. Speak the words.

707
00:51:53.140 --> 00:51:54.980
Whitecap Bay.

708
00:51:55.300 --> 00:51:57.980
Aye, Whitecap Bay.

709
00:51:58.060 --> 00:52:02.420
And every worthless seaman
fears the name,
and rightly so,

710
00:52:02.540 --> 00:52:04.860
though few know why
or dare to ask.

711
00:52:04.940 --> 00:52:06.620
Be the stories true?

712
00:52:06.700 --> 00:52:08.700
Say what robs you of
your staunch heart, Gibbs,

713
00:52:08.820 --> 00:52:12.140
or forever leave it
to the wider fields of fancy.

714
00:52:14.700 --> 00:52:16.300
Mermaids, Captain.

715
00:52:16.380 --> 00:52:18.180
Aye. Mermaids.
[crew murmuring]

716
00:52:18.300 --> 00:52:22.500
Sea ghouls,
devil fish, dreadful in
hunger for flesh of man.

717
00:52:22.620 --> 00:52:25.900
Mermaid waters,
that be our path.

718
00:52:26.340 --> 00:52:27.740
Cling to your soul, Gibbs,

719
00:52:27.820 --> 00:52:31.100
as mermaids be given
to take the rest...

720
00:52:31.620 --> 00:52:34.540
...to the bone.
[crew chattering]

721
00:52:34.620 --> 00:52:37.780
Steady! Steady, men!
Find your courage,

722
00:52:37.900 --> 00:52:40.060
or be ready
to purpose your fear!

723
00:52:40.140 --> 00:52:42.140
[man] Save yourselves!

724
00:52:44.820 --> 00:52:47.980
[man] Man overboard!
Nay! A deserter.

725
00:52:48.100 --> 00:52:49.860
Come about.
Nay!

726
00:52:50.820 --> 00:52:55.020
Gentlemen, I shall not ask
any more of any man than what

727
00:52:55.100 --> 00:52:59.620
that man can deliver,
but I do ask this:
Are we not king's men?

728
00:53:00.300 --> 00:53:01.460
[all quietly] Aye.

729
00:53:01.540 --> 00:53:04.100
On the king's mission?
[all louder] Aye.

730
00:53:04.220 --> 00:53:08.140
I did not note any fear
in the eyes of the Spanish
as they passed us by.

731
00:53:08.220 --> 00:53:10.500
Are we not king's men?
[all shout] Aye!

732
00:53:10.620 --> 00:53:14.460
Aye! Hands all off,
and bear away!

733
00:53:14.580 --> 00:53:17.620
Stave on ahead
to Whitecap Bay!

734
00:53:18.740 --> 00:53:21.700
[man] Bear on, Whitecap Bay!

735
00:53:29.540 --> 00:53:32.700
[man plays up-tempo
guitar music]

736
00:53:32.820 --> 00:53:38.020
<i>Hola...</i>
Come. Little drink?

737
00:53:38.620 --> 00:53:41.500
Wine, music, candlelight.

738
00:53:41.900 --> 00:53:44.580
I think we've traveled down
this road before, Jack.

739
00:53:44.660 --> 00:53:45.860
Yes, we have.

740
00:53:47.100 --> 00:53:48.500
I remember it well.

741
00:53:50.300 --> 00:53:54.580
Winding, twisting and
turning, gyrating, writhing.

742
00:53:55.140 --> 00:53:57.220
Incessant writhing.

743
00:53:58.060 --> 00:53:59.540
Do you recall
Saint Dominique?

744
00:54:00.860 --> 00:54:02.500
La Martinique.

745
00:54:02.580 --> 00:54:04.540
I tried to kill you
in Saint Dominique.

746
00:54:05.100 --> 00:54:06.380
Either or.

747
00:54:06.980 --> 00:54:09.300
Hardly appropriate
for a first mate.

748
00:54:09.820 --> 00:54:12.900
Was I the first?
I've often wondered.

749
00:54:13.660 --> 00:54:16.900
You can be so charming
when you want something, Jack.

750
00:54:17.380 --> 00:54:19.500
The trick is
finding out what.

751
00:54:20.900 --> 00:54:23.020
[Jack] The truth,
then, is it?

752
00:54:23.140 --> 00:54:26.020
Blackbeard has served
his purpose.

753
00:54:26.100 --> 00:54:28.700
You and I can go to
the Fountain together,

754
00:54:28.780 --> 00:54:30.380
where we shall
bathe one another

755
00:54:30.460 --> 00:54:32.140
in equal shares of fame

756
00:54:32.260 --> 00:54:34.180
and other assorted
debaucheries.

757
00:54:34.300 --> 00:54:37.140
And I'll tell you
the ritual of the Fountain.

758
00:54:37.420 --> 00:54:40.140
Yes. The profane ritual.

759
00:54:40.620 --> 00:54:41.700
[gasps]

760
00:54:42.140 --> 00:54:44.740
[inhales deeply]
Can I trust you, Jack?

761
00:54:44.860 --> 00:54:47.220
I need you on my side.

762
00:54:47.300 --> 00:54:49.660
Oh, my dearest Angelica.

763
00:54:49.780 --> 00:54:53.300
You and I are as
thick as thieves, love.

764
00:54:53.420 --> 00:54:54.980
Tell me the rules.

765
00:54:57.980 --> 00:55:01.300
Water from the
Fountain of Youth.

766
00:55:03.300 --> 00:55:06.500
The shimmering tear
of a mermaid.

767
00:55:07.060 --> 00:55:09.940
The silver chalices
of Ponce de Leon.

768
00:55:10.020 --> 00:55:13.780
Uh-huh?
With these items...

769
00:55:13.860 --> 00:55:16.140
Yes?
With these items,

770
00:55:16.220 --> 00:55:19.700
you may take all the years
of life from another, Jack.

771
00:55:20.700 --> 00:55:23.540
Eh?
You know what that means.

772
00:55:23.620 --> 00:55:26.420
We cannot go alone,
you and I.

773
00:55:26.500 --> 00:55:29.100
The ritual
requires a victim.

774
00:55:30.700 --> 00:55:34.940
That is unfortunate.
Yes, it is.

775
00:55:35.340 --> 00:55:38.540
I find my desire for the
Fountain greatly lessened.

776
00:55:39.620 --> 00:55:42.660
But there is something
on board you do want.

777
00:55:48.380 --> 00:55:49.900
What about Blackbeard?

778
00:55:49.980 --> 00:55:53.500
He's in the chart room.
We'll have to be quick.

779
00:55:53.620 --> 00:55:56.060
[door creaks]

780
00:56:02.140 --> 00:56:05.340
He keeps each ship
as a prize.

781
00:56:06.380 --> 00:56:11.820
You help me, and I
promise you your pick.

782
00:56:11.900 --> 00:56:14.940
Though I think I know
the one you will choose.

783
00:56:17.580 --> 00:56:18.620
[thundering]

784
00:56:20.540 --> 00:56:22.860
The Black Pearl
<i>in a bottle?</i>

785
00:56:23.340 --> 00:56:25.180
Why is the Black Pearl
<i>in a bottle?</i>

786
00:56:28.540 --> 00:56:30.740
[chittering]
[shouts] Oh!

787
00:56:30.820 --> 00:56:33.180
He's even more
annoying in miniature.

788
00:56:34.060 --> 00:56:37.820
Do we have a deal, Jack?
Angelica, I know you.

789
00:56:38.060 --> 00:56:41.020
You are not going to steal
the life of some innocent man.

790
00:56:41.540 --> 00:56:43.820
What about the
one-legged man?

791
00:56:45.620 --> 00:56:48.220
[door creaks]
I need years, Jack.

792
00:56:49.420 --> 00:56:53.020
Not for me. For my father.

793
00:56:55.460 --> 00:56:57.980
I am truly the daughter
of Blackbeard.

794
00:56:58.100 --> 00:57:01.180
[inhales] You've fallen
for your own con, love.

795
00:57:01.260 --> 00:57:03.220
No, he is my father.

796
00:57:03.300 --> 00:57:05.380
The lies I told you
were not lies.

797
00:57:06.940 --> 00:57:08.980
You lied to me
by telling me the truth?

798
00:57:10.020 --> 00:57:12.060
Yes.
That's very good.

799
00:57:12.140 --> 00:57:14.980
May I use that?
I'm sure you will, anyway.

800
00:57:15.060 --> 00:57:16.820
Of course I will.

801
00:57:17.100 --> 00:57:20.660
So, will you not
give up this quest?

802
00:57:20.940 --> 00:57:23.980
I want a father, Jack.
I haven't had one.

803
00:57:24.860 --> 00:57:28.460
Angelica,
your father, Blackbeard...

804
00:57:29.780 --> 00:57:31.300
...he is evil,

805
00:57:31.380 --> 00:57:33.660
and he will kill you
given the chance.

806
00:57:33.740 --> 00:57:36.900
He cannot be saved.
And who are you to set

807
00:57:36.980 --> 00:57:38.780
the limits on redemption?

808
00:57:39.220 --> 00:57:42.740
You stole years of my life,
Jack. You owe me.

809
00:57:42.820 --> 00:57:45.700
And you are en route
to getting yourself killed,

810
00:57:45.780 --> 00:57:48.220
and I am not inclined
to stand by and watch.

811
00:57:48.300 --> 00:57:52.860
[man shouting] Whitecap Bay!
[bell ringing]

812
00:57:57.620 --> 00:58:00.780
All hands on deck!
Set to the longboats!

813
00:58:03.180 --> 00:58:06.380
[indistinct chatter]
[Blackbeard]
Lay 'em out flat!

814
00:58:06.460 --> 00:58:11.020
No tangles. Make 'em look
pretty for our dainty guests.

815
00:58:11.100 --> 00:58:15.460
We're gonna need light.
A lot of light.

816
00:58:16.780 --> 00:58:18.100
Come!

817
00:58:39.380 --> 00:58:44.820
Smell that? Whale oil.
Stuff burns like
a miracle from God.

818
00:58:44.900 --> 00:58:48.780
Can you make it work?
Made by the English.

819
00:58:48.860 --> 00:58:50.260
Let's not get our hopes up.

820
00:58:53.940 --> 00:58:56.180
[wood creaking]

821
00:59:00.940 --> 00:59:03.380
The old moon in
the arms of the new one.

822
00:59:03.460 --> 00:59:05.060
First of the summer.

823
00:59:05.500 --> 00:59:08.380
Perfect for hunting
a mermaid's tear.

824
00:59:21.100 --> 00:59:24.780
We're doomed. They be drawn
to man-made light.

825
00:59:24.940 --> 00:59:27.860
Sharks?
Worse than sharks, boy.

826
00:59:27.980 --> 00:59:30.220
There'll be mermaids upon us
within the hour,

827
00:59:30.300 --> 00:59:33.660
you mark my words.
And we're the bait.

828
00:59:38.780 --> 00:59:42.500
I heard it said a kiss
from a mermaid protects
a sailor from drowning.

829
00:59:42.580 --> 00:59:46.380
Don't be a fool!
Mermaids are all female, son,

830
00:59:46.460 --> 00:59:48.980
and lovely
as a dream of heaven.

831
00:59:49.340 --> 00:59:53.340
But when it comes time
to churn butter,
so to speak,

832
00:59:53.420 --> 00:59:55.780
they snatch a sailor
out of a boat

833
00:59:55.860 --> 00:59:58.900
or off the deck of a ship,
have their way,

834
00:59:59.100 --> 01:00:04.060
and then the sailors
are pulled to bottom
and drowned and eaten.

835
01:00:04.660 --> 01:00:07.940
Or, sometimes,
the other way around.

836
01:00:08.900 --> 01:00:11.900
[Gunner] Sing.
What?

837
01:00:13.180 --> 01:00:15.420
They like to hear singing.

838
01:00:19.300 --> 01:00:23.300
<i>♪ My name is Maria ♪</i>

839
01:00:23.380 --> 01:00:26.620
<i>♪ A merchant's daughter fair ♪</i>

840
01:00:26.700 --> 01:00:27.660
Louder.

841
01:00:27.740 --> 01:00:29.820
<i>♪ And I have left</i>
<i>my parents ♪</i>

842
01:00:29.900 --> 01:00:33.500
<i>♪ And 3,000 pounds a year ♪</i>

843
01:00:33.820 --> 01:00:36.220
<i>♪ My heart is</i>
<i>pierced by Cupid ♪</i>
[cocks gun]

844
01:00:36.300 --> 01:00:40.300
<i>♪ I disdain</i>
<i>all glittering gold ♪</i>

845
01:00:40.660 --> 01:00:43.980
<i>[all] ♪ There is nothing</i>
<i>can console me ♪</i>

846
01:00:44.060 --> 01:00:47.500
<i>♪ But my jolly sailor bold ♪</i>

847
01:00:49.660 --> 01:00:52.940
<i>♪ My heart</i>
<i>is pierced by Cupid ♪</i>

848
01:00:53.060 --> 01:00:55.900
<i>♪ I disdain</i>
<i>all glittering gold ♪</i>

849
